VALUES
  ('pine-barrens-leeds-point', 'Leeds Point - Birthplace of the Jersey Devil', 'Leeds Point', 'Leeds Point Road', 'NJ', 39.4956, -74.4133, 'other', 'This remote area in the Pine Barrens is the legendary birthplace of the Jersey Devil, New Jersey''s most famous cryptid. The vast 1.1 million acre wilderness has been named one of the most haunted locations in America by Conde Nast Traveler.', 'According to folklore, in 1735 a Pine Barrens resident named Jane Leeds (aka "Mother Leeds") became pregnant with her 13th child. In frustration, she cursed the child, crying out that it would be the devil. The creature born was described as having a horse''s head, bat wings, cloven hooves, and a forked tail. It flew up the chimney and has haunted the Pine Barrens ever since. Sightings occur regularly, with the creature said to attack livestock and terrify travelers.', 1735, 'https://usghostadventures.com/atlantic-city-ghost-tour/the-new-jersey-pine-barren-ghosts/'),

  ('batsto-village', 'Batsto Village', 'Hammonton', '31 Batsto Road', 'NJ', 39.6431, -74.6492, 'other', 'A remarkably preserved 19th-century iron-making village deep in the Pine Barrens, Batsto was founded in 1766 and supplied the Continental Army during the Revolutionary War. The 33 historic buildings include the Batsto Mansion with 32 rooms.', 'The village is haunted by multiple spirits including Frank Peck, a mysterious "Water Wizard," and whispers of the Richards family who owned the ironworks. Native American presence echoes through tales of Indian Ann, whose basket-weaving legacy adds mystical depth. Floating light orbs are frequently seen in the cemetery. The legendary Jersey Devil has been sighted in the surrounding Wharton State Forest. Annual "Jersey Devil Bound" twilight hikes explore the paranormal activity.', 1766, 'https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/batsto-village-new-jersey-ghost-town/'),

  ('ongs-hat', 'Ong''s Hat Ghost Town', 'Pemberton Township', 'Ong''s Hat Road', 'NJ', 39.8833, -74.5500, 'other', 'New Jersey''s most notorious ghost town is barely visible today, with only a few foundations remaining in the Pine Barrens. At its peak, it consisted of only several structures, yet it has spawned one of the strangest conspiracy theories in New Jersey history.', 'According to an elaborate urban legend, Ong''s Hat contains a portal to another dimension. Conspiracy theorists claim scientists at a secret laboratory here discovered interdimensional travel in the 1980s and escaped to a parallel earth. The remote location, surrounded by Pine Barrens wilderness, contributes to reports of strange lights, unexplained sounds, and an overwhelming sense of being watched by something not of this world.', 1700, 'https://www.onlyinyourstate.com/experiences/new-jersey/nj-ongs-hat'),

  ('burnt-mill-road-atco', 'Burnt Mill Road - The Atco Ghost', 'Atco', 'Burnt Mill Road', 'NJ', 39.7522, -74.8831, 'other', 'A lonely stretch of road in the Pine Barrens near Atco has become infamous for supernatural encounters. The area was once home to sawmills and scattered settlements that have long since vanished into the forest.', 'The road is haunted by the ghost of a little boy, believed to be the victim of a hit-and-run accident. He now wanders Burnt Mill Road at night, searching for his killer. Motorists report seeing a child-sized figure in their headlights that vanishes when approached. Other Pine Barrens ghosts reported nearby include a blonde woman in white, a spectral black dog, and the ever-present Jersey Devil. The sound of childish laughter echoes through the trees on foggy nights.', 1900, 'https://usghostadventures.com/atlantic-city-ghost-tour/the-new-jersey-pine-barren-ghosts/'),

  ('allaire-village', 'Historic Allaire Village', 'Farmingdale', '4263 Atlantic Avenue', 'NJ', 40.1528, -74.1297, 'museum', 'A beautifully preserved 19th-century iron-working village within Allaire State Park. Founded as Howell Works, the community included a blast furnace, workers'' homes, a church, general store, and the grand "Big House" manor. James P. Allaire died on the property in 1858.', 'Multiple spirits haunt the village, most notably Hal Allaire, son of the founder. Oscar Cheesman Smith, the iron works manager, haunts the Manager''s House and enjoys spelling out names with children''s toy blocks. Workers report candlelight and faces in the windows of the Big House after closing. Chairs move on their own, strange voices echo through buildings, and images appear in mirrors that aren''t actually there. Benjamin Marks, described as "a nasty, angry man who wears boots," is sensed by psychics.', 1822, 'https://weirdnj.com/stories/garden-state-ghosts/allaires-haunted-big-house/');

