  ('nassau-hall-princeton', 'Nassau Hall', 'Princeton', 'Nassau Street', 'NJ', 40.3485, -74.6593, 'university', 'The oldest building on the Princeton University campus, Nassau Hall served as the temporary capital of the United States in 1783. The building has witnessed the Revolutionary War, the signing of the Treaty of Paris, and over 250 years of academic history.', 'Aaron Burr Sr., Princeton''s second president, keeps mostly to the site of his old office, haunting Nassau Hall and checking up on the progress of his beloved college. His presence is felt throughout the historic building. James Madison is also said to haunt the campus. The building''s role in American history - from housing the Continental Congress to surviving British cannon fire - has left layers of spectral energy within its walls.', 1756, 'https://www.princetonmagazine.com/top-ten-haunted-places-in-princeton/'),

  ('rockefeller-college-princeton', 'Rockefeller College (Rocky)', 'Princeton', 'Rockefeller College', 'NJ', 40.3478, -74.6558, 'university', 'This Collegiate Gothic dormitory is built on what was once a cemetery for the FitzRandolph family. When Italian stonemasons began digging at the site, they made a disturbing discovery buried beneath the grounds.', 'Workers found skeletons during construction, which were buried in a wall of the archway to the quadrangle. Two students, a married couple, reported that their room atop the archway had a couch and painting that would move independently. The spirits of the FitzRandolph family, disturbed from their eternal rest, are believed to cause the paranormal activity. Cold spots and unexplained sounds are regularly reported in the archway rooms.', 1927, 'https://www.princetonmagazine.com/top-ten-haunted-places-in-princeton/'),

  ('nassau-inn-princeton', 'Nassau Inn', 'Princeton', '10 Palmer Square', 'NJ', 40.3502, -74.6601, 'hotel', 'A historic hotel on Palmer Square that has served Princeton visitors since 1937, though earlier inns have stood on this site for centuries. The elegant property maintains its colonial charm while harboring Revolutionary War era spirits.', 'More than one guest has reported seeing a Revolutionary War soldier on one of the floors. He''s not angry, witnesses say, but has a curious expression as if confused about the modern surroundings. A woman in period dress has been seen going upstairs from the lobby to the second floor private meeting rooms, then vanishing. The long history of military activity in Princeton during the Revolution seems to have left permanent residents.', 1937, 'https://www.princetonmagazine.com/top-ten-haunted-places-in-princeton/'),

  ('thomas-clarke-house', 'Thomas Clarke House', 'Princeton', '500 Mercer Road', 'NJ', 40.3372, -74.6553, 'museum', 'This historic house at the Princeton Battlefield served as a hospital during the American Revolution. Brigadier General Hugh Mercer was brought here after being bayoneted seven times during the Battle of Princeton on January 3, 1777, and died nine days later.', 'In one of the upstairs bedrooms where General Mercer suffered his final days, custodians and visitors have reported getting an unusual feeling around their necks. This sensation may be connected to the fact that Mercer''s cravat was removed while he was in the house. General Mercer''s spirit seems reluctant to leave the place where he spent his final painful days, his presence felt most strongly near his deathbed.', 1772, 'https://www.princetonmagazine.com/top-ten-haunted-places-in-princeton/'),

  ('princeton-cemetery', 'Princeton Cemetery', 'Princeton', '29 Greenview Avenue', 'NJ', 40.3469, -74.6572, 'cemetery', 'This renowned resting place dates back to 1757 and contains the graves of notables including President Grover Cleveland, Aaron Burr, and the parents of the Menendez Brothers. The historic cemetery is part of guided ghost tours.', 'More than one visitor has reported strange sensations at the cemetery, particularly near the graves of its most famous residents. Aaron Burr Jr.''s spirit has been encountered not only here but on campus and as far away as New York City. Paranormal investigators with dowsing rods and thermal meters regularly detect unexplained activity. The concentration of Revolutionary War figures and university presidents creates a powerful spiritual energy.', 1757, 'https://princetontourcompany.com/tours/cemetery-ghost-tour/'),

  ('the-barracks-princeton', 'The Barracks', 'Princeton', '32 Edgehill Street', 'NJ', 40.3511, -74.6619, 'mansion', 'This stone house built by Declaration of Independence signer Richard Stockton is thought to be Princeton''s oldest surviving structure. During the Revolution, it housed soldiers and witnessed the aftermath of Washington''s surprise attack on Trenton.', 'Following Washington''s Christmas Day attack across the Delaware in 1776, a Hessian soldier fled with his contingent from Trenton to Princeton, where he finally died while seeking shelter in this house on Edgehill Street. He has haunted the building ever since. Legend has it that he appears in the fireplace every Christmas Eve, still trying to warm himself from that bitter winter when the Revolution turned against the British.', 1696, 'https://www.princetonmagazine.com/top-ten-haunted-places-in-princeton/');

