  ('jockey-hollow', 'Jockey Hollow', 'Morristown', '586 Tempe Wick Road', 'NJ', 40.7608, -74.5408, 'battlefield', 'Part of Morristown National Historical Park, Jockey Hollow was the site of the Continental Army''s winter encampment in 1779-1780 - a winter even more brutal than Valley Forge. A boulder marks the mass grave of roughly 100 soldiers who died of exposure and disease.', 'Hikers, visitors, and reenactors report colonial soldiers marching lockstep through dense trees, unexplainable fife and drum music, and shadowy figures dashing among the replica soldier huts. The translucent apparition of a woman in white carrying a lantern is seen on foggy nights - perhaps searching for a lost loved one among the frozen dead. The concentration of suffering during that terrible winter has left an indelible mark on this ground.', 1779, 'https://www.battlefields.org/learn/head-tilting-history/haunting-encounters-revolutionary-ghouls'),

  ('ford-mansion', 'Ford Mansion (Washington''s Headquarters)', 'Morristown', '230 Morris Street', 'NJ', 40.7672, -74.4758, 'mansion', 'This Georgian-style mansion built in 1774 served as General George Washington''s headquarters during the winter of 1779-1780. Washington, Martha, five aides-de-camp including Alexander Hamilton, and eighteen servants lived here for 200 days.', 'Paranormal investigators have documented ghost activity including unexplained photos, audio recordings, and developing theories about Revolutionary War secrets harbored by spirits. The Ford family resided here for three generations, and some believe their ghosts along with Washington''s staff still inhabit the mansion. Cold spots, footsteps on wooden floors, and the sense of being watched by figures in colonial dress are commonly reported.', 1774, 'https://patch.com/new-jersey/morristown/experience-ghostly-revelations-ford-mansion-oct-15'),

  ('old-bernardsville-library', 'Old Bernardsville Public Library', 'Bernardsville', '1 Anderson Hill Road', 'NJ', 40.7206, -74.5714, 'museum', 'Built in 1710 as the Vealtown Tavern, this building hosted George Washington and his troops during the Revolutionary War. It later served as Bernardsville''s public library and is one of the oldest structures in the area.', 'Phyllis Parker, the innkeeper''s daughter, fell in love with Dr. Byram, a dashing guest who was revealed to be a British spy. When he was hanged and his body delivered to the tavern in a coffin in 1777, Phyllis opened the crate, screamed, and went insane. Her cries have been heard in the reading room since 1875. Staff even issued Phyllis a library card. The last sighting was in 1989 when a 3-year-old boy said hello to "the lady in the white dress."', 1710, 'https://patch.com/new-jersey/bernardsville-bedminster/phyllis-bernardsville-librarys-ghost'),

  ('gallows-hill-road', 'Gallows Hill Road', 'Basking Ridge', 'Gallows Hill Road and Brookside Place', 'NJ', 40.6817, -74.5689, 'other', 'At the corner of Gallows Hill Road and Brookside Place once stood a giant hanging tree where Revolutionary War spies were executed. Though the tree is gone, the site retains its dark energy from centuries of public executions.', 'Locals say you can still see ghostly movement here from a distance - figures swinging from branches that no longer exist. The energy of those executed during the Revolution lingers at this crossroads. Drivers passing at night report seeing shadows of hanged men silhouetted against the sky. The condemned seem unable to rest, their spirits trapped at the place of their violent deaths.', 1777, 'https://morristowngreen.com/2016/10/27/the-morristown-ghost-or-beware-of-ghosts-promising-gifts/'),

  ('publick-house-chester', 'The Publick House', 'Chester', '111 Main Street', 'NJ', 40.7847, -74.6942, 'restaurant', 'Originally the 1810 Brick Hotel, the Publick House is a beloved dining destination in historic Chester. The building has served travelers along this route for over two centuries, accumulating stories and spirits along the way.', 'The restaurant is said to be haunted by apparitions, growling noises, cold spots, phantom perfumes, and other eerie phenomena. Staff and diners have reported unexplained activity throughout the historic building. The spirits seem connected to the building''s long history as a hotel and tavern, where countless travelers passed through - some perhaps never leaving.', 1810, 'https://mmtlibrary.org/nj-history-genealogy/guides-for-research-pathfinders/ghosts-and-haunts-of-new-jersey/'),

  ('the-hermitage', 'The Hermitage', 'Ho-Ho-Kus', '335 North Franklin Turnpike', 'NJ', 41.0003, -74.1014, 'mansion', 'A National Historic Landmark, the Hermitage was the site of Aaron Burr''s 1782 marriage to Theodosia Prevost. The property hosted George Washington, James Monroe, Lafayette, and Alexander Hamilton during the Revolutionary War.', 'The Rosencrantz family, later owners, seem to linger. An African American woman holding a baby has emerged from the barn. Piano music echoes through the empty house. The ghost of Mary Elizabeth Rosencrantz, the property''s last resident, still lives here according to mediums. A photograph captured the full-body apparition of a little girl, identified as Mary Warner Rosencrantz, on the front lawn. Seances and ghost tours are held regularly.', 1740, 'https://craigmcmanus.com/ghosts-of-the-hermitage/');

